messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full HTTP request path:
- /printshops/{id}/pricetable/covers

HTTP methods acceptance (based on the code):
- Are all methods acceptable? No. The code only defines POST for addNewCoverItem and PUT for the related edit method on the same path.
- HEAD: false
- POST: true
- OPTIONS: true (Spring handles OPTIONS for mapped paths by listing allowed methods)
- TRACE: false
- GET: false
- PUT: true
- DELETE: false
- PATCH: false

Explanation:
- The addNewCoverItem method is mapped with @RequestMapping(value = "/printshops/{id}/pricetable/covers", method = RequestMethod.POST), and there is a separate editCoverItem method mapped to the same path with PUT. No other HTTP methods are mapped to this path in the code.
- Therefore, POST and PUT are the accepted methods for /printshops/{id}/pricetable/covers.
- HEAD is not explicitly mapped; in Spring, it is not exposed unless GET is mapped or framework handles it implicitly; since neither GET nor a HEAD-specific mapping exists here, HEAD is not considered acceptable.
- OPTIONS is typically automatically handled by Spring for mapped paths, so it is acceptable.
- TRACE, GET, DELETE, PATCH are not mapped for this path, so they are not acceptable.
